Akamai CEO doubles his bonus in 2014 — to $2









E-Mail

Share via e-mail




To



Add a message



Your e-mail







Facebook


Twitter


Google+


LinkedIn




 Comments



Print



The Boston Globe

Tweet

Share









By Hiawatha Bray
	Globe Staff 
	April 02, 2015










Kayana Szymczak for The Boston Globe
F. Thomson Leighton.



By most measures, Akamai Technologies Inc. had a successful year in 2014. Net income was up 14 percent, revenue up 24 percent. So the company’s board rewarded the chief executive, F. Thomson Leighton, by doubling his bonus — to $2.Leighton, like Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg or the late Apple Inc. chief Steve Jobs, takes a salary of $1 per year. But despite the fact that his cash compensation amounted to $3 last year, don’t expect to find him shopping at Family Dollar. According to Akamai’s proxy statement, filed Thursday, Leighton took home stock worth $7.5 million, up from the $6 million in stock he got in 2013.
Advertisement

 
Akamai runs a global data network that speeds the delivery of Internet content for major websites worldwide.Other Akamai executives got notable raises, much of it in cash. The president of worldwide operations, Robert Hughes, and the president of products and development, Rick McConnell, 
earned more than $510,000 in salary. But each also collected about $3 million in Akamai stock as well as almost $900,000 in incentive compensation.



      Get Talking Points in your inbox:
    

        An afternoon recap of the day’s most important business news, delivered weekdays.






Sign Up





    Thank you for signing up!
    Sign up for more newsletters here


Akamai’s proxy says that Leighton’s compensation takes into consideration his “past compensation history, his significant equity holdings, peer group practices, and the desire to include significant performance-based vehicles as the majority of his pay package.” 
According to Bloomberg, Leighton’s “significant” Akamai holdings are worth $223 million.The tradition of the “dollar-a-year man” began during World War I, when top executives took government jobs at virtually no salary to help the war effort. Some high-profile executives continued the tradition in the private sector, but they almost always supplement their skimpy paychecks with ample grants of stocks, options, and other financial benefits.Hiawatha Bray can be reached at hiawatha.bray@globe.com. Follow him on Twitter @GlobeTechLab.












